Project Name: House Price Prediction using Advance Regression Techniques¶

Exploratory data Analysis (EDA)¶

Dataset to downloaded from the below link https://www.kaggle.com/c/house-prices-advanced-regression-techniques/data

Lifecycle of a Data Science Project¶

  1. Data Analysis-Exploratory data Analysis (EDA)
  2. Feature Engineering
  3. Feature Selection
  4. Model Building
  5. Model Deployment

Relationship between missing values and Sales Price¶

Since they are many missing values Let's plot some diagram for this relationship

In [11]:
for feature in features_with_na:
    data = dataset.copy()  #Copy of Dataset,Any changes made in the original DataFrame will NOT be reflected in the copy
    
    # let's make a variable that indicates 1 if the observation was missing or zero otherwise
    data[feature] = np.where(data[feature].isnull(), 1, 0)
    
    # let's calculate the mean SalePrice, where the information is missing or present
    data.groupby(feature)['SalePrice'].median().plot.bar()
    plt.title(feature)
    plt.show()

Here, with the relation between the missing values and the dependent variable is clearly visible.So We need to replace these 'nan' values with something meaningful, which I will do in the Feature Engineering Phase.¶

From the above dataset some of the features like Id is not required.¶

Temporal Variables(Eg: Datetime Variables)¶

From the Dataset we have 4 year variables(YearBuilt, YearRemodAdd,YrSold, GarageYrBlt). We have extract information from the datetime variables like no of years or no of days. Scenerio can be: To calculate difference in years between the year the house was built and the year the house was sold. I will be performing this analysis in the Feature Engineering Phase.

## Here we will compare the difference between All years feature with SalePrice

for feature in year_feature:
    if feature!='YrSold':
        data=dataset.copy()
        
        ## We will capture the difference between year variable and year the house was sold for
        data[feature]=data['YrSold']-data[feature]

        plt.scatter(data[feature],data['SalePrice'])
        plt.xlabel(feature)
        plt.ylabel('SalePrice')
        plt.show()

In [39]:
## Analyse the continuous values to understand the distribution with hitogram.

for feature in continuous_feature:
    data=dataset.copy()
    data[feature].hist(bins=25)
    plt.xlabel(feature)
    plt.ylabel("Count")
    plt.title(feature)
    plt.show()

As we can see from above graphs, our data is not normaly distributed fully and it is skewed.¶

In [43]:
## Here, We will use logarithmic transformation, It makes our skewed original data more normal. 
## It improves linearity between our dependent and independent variables. It boosts validity of our statistical analyses.


for feature in continuous_feature:
    data=dataset.copy()
    if 0 in data[feature].unique():
        pass
    else:
        data[feature]=np.log(data[feature])
        data['SalePrice']=np.log(data['SalePrice'])
        plt.scatter(data[feature],data['SalePrice'])
        plt.xlabel(feature)
        plt.ylabel('SalesPrice')
        plt.title(feature)
        plt.show()

As we can see from above graphs, We can see monotonic relation and positive co-relation between variables.¶

Outliers¶

In [51]:
for feature in continuous_feature:
    data=dataset.copy()
    if 0 in data[feature].unique():
        pass
    else:
        data[feature]=np.log(data[feature])
        data.boxplot(column=feature)
        plt.ylabel(feature)
        plt.title(feature)
        plt.show()

In the above boxplots, We can see there is so many outliers, which I will be removing in feature engineering part.¶

Note: Boxplot will not work for Categorical features, ony works with contnous variable features.
